                    <msContents>
                        <summary>A major work on religious obligations and moral duties, extracted
                            from the author's Arabic work <title xml:lang="ara-Latn-x-lc">Iḥyā’
                                ‘Ulūm al-Dīn</title><title xml:lang="ara">احياء علوم الدين</title>
                            <name><persName xml:lang="ara-Latn-x-lc">Ghazzālī,
                                1058-1111</persName></name> was considered to be the greatest
                            authority on Shafi‘ī branch of Islamic law, and was entitled Hujjat
                            al-Islam. He wrote about one hundred books and treatises, mostly in
                            Arabic, but also a few in Persian, including the present work, which is
                            a Persian abridgement of his Arabic work, <title
                                xml:lang="ara-Latn-x-lc">Iḥyā ‘Ulūm al-Dīn</title><title
                                xml:lang="ara">احيا علوم الدين</title>, divided into four rukn. Volume one, in 93 folios
                            and 2 fly leaves, contain a general brief preface <locus from="1v"
                                to="1v">ff.lv-3v</locus>, an introduction on cognition, divided into
                            four ‘unvān from <locus from="3v" to="3v">3v</locus> to <locus
                                from="43r" to="43r">43r</locus> and the first rukn entitled ‘bādāt,
                            divided into ten aṣl from<locus from="43r" to="43r">f. 43r</locus> to
                                <locus from="93r" to="93r">f. 93r</locus>.</summary>
                        <!-- summary description -->
                        <msItem>
